Diagnosis:
The largest Australasian micronectid, easily recognized by size, conically produced head, distinct hemelytral patterning (
Figs. 31aâ€“b
), and distinct male genitalia (
Figs. 33aâ€“g
). Females recognized on the combination of size, hemelytral patterning, prothoracic lobe (
Fig. 32a
), and metaxyphus (
Fig. 32b
). Possibly confused only with 

Micronecta robusta
Hale

based on size, however, readily distinguished by characters given in the key.

